# Reflection

This assignment required translating system requirements and use cases into Agile artifacts such as user stories, a product backlog, and a sprint plan. One of the main challenges I faced was prioritizing features using the MoSCoW method. Since I am both the developer and the stakeholder in this project, it was difficult to objectively decide which features were truly essential and which could be delayed. At times, I wanted to include more features in the “Must-have” category because they all seemed important from a system perspective. However, I had to consciously step back and focus on what is necessary for a Minimum Viable Product (MVP).

Another challenge was estimating story points. Without practical implementation experience for the system, it was difficult to accurately judge the effort required for each user story. I had to rely on logical reasoning and assumptions about complexity, which made me aware of how estimation in Agile can be subjective, especially in the early stages of development.

Aligning Agile practices with stakeholder needs was also interesting in this case, as I had to simulate the role of a client while also acting as the developer. This created internal resistance, as I had to question my own decisions and ensure that I was not overcomplicating the system. For example, features like notifications and reporting seemed useful, but I had to recognize that they are not critical for the first version of the system.

Using GitHub Agile tools was a valuable learning experience. Creating issues for user stories, organizing them into a project board, and assigning them to a sprint milestone helped me understand how real-world Agile teams manage their workflow. Moving tasks between “To Do,” “In Progress,” and “Done” provided a clear visual representation of progress and made the development process more structured.

Overall, this assignment improved my understanding of Agile methodology and how to break down system requirements into manageable tasks. It highlighted the importance of prioritization, estimation, and iterative development. I also learned that Agile is not just about tools, but about making informed decisions and continuously refining the system based on what delivers the most value.
